            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Alex Volkov\u2019s story began not in San Francisco, but thousands of miles away in a Siberian orphanage. Adopted at age three by a loving Chinese-American couple, he was brought to a new life in the fog-draped avenues of the Sunset District. His name, a remnant of a past he couldn't remember, stood in gentle contrast to the Cantonese spoken in his warm, bustling home. Growing up, Alex was never academic; he was practical, observant, and more comfortable fixing a bicycle chain than reading a textbook. He absorbed the rhythms of the city from its streets, not a classroom.\n\nAfter graduating from high school, Alex felt adrift. While his friends left for college, he worked a series of odd jobs, from stocking shelves at a local market to washing dishes in a Clement Street restaurant. The turning point came a few years later when his uncle, a longtime MUNI mechanic, suggested he apply to be a bus operator. The process was long, but the promise of stability, a union salary, and a pension was a powerful lure. Landing the job was one of the proudest moments of his life; it was a role that felt essential, a way to serve the city that had given him everything.\n\nNow, at 44, Alex\u2019s life is one of dependable routine. He lives in a small, tidy apartment in the Inner Richmond, just a short bus ride\u2014usually the 1-California\u2014from the depot. His days are dictated by his shift schedule, often starting before dawn. From the driver\u2019s seat of his bus, he possesses a unique, ground-level view of San Francisco. He knows the regulars on his route, the subtle shifts in the neighborhoods, and the hum of the city waking and sleeping. His social life is simple, centered around a few close friends\u2014fellow operators with whom he shares a dark sense of humor and an unspoken understanding of their shared work.\n\nQuiet and introspective, Alex doesn't harbor grand ambitions. His dream is a humble one: to save enough to take a trip back to Siberia. He has no desire to search for his birth parents, but rather a quiet need to see the landscape of his origin, to stand in the place where his improbable journey began. For Alex, it's about acknowledging the starting line of a life he is profoundly grateful to be living in the heart of San Francisco."
        },
