            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being seven, sitting at the kitchen table as his mother\u2019s nimble hands folded sticky rice and fillings into bamboo leaves. The air was thick with savory steam. She paused, looked at him, and said his name, \u201cAlex,\u201d her voice wrapping it in a Cantonese accent that made it sound like home. In that moment, he felt the strangeness of his Russian name not as a disconnect, but as a special thread woven into the fabric of her love. It taught him that family was a thing you build, not just a thing you're born into.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, his hands were perpetually raw from the dish pit of a restaurant on Clement Street. One night, standing in the alley for a breath of cool air, he watched a car of his old high school friends drive past, laughing, on their way somewhere exciting. A wave of shame and aimlessness washed over him. It wasn't jealousy, but a cold, hard realization that he was stuck. That single moment in the lamplit alley hardened his resolve to find a job with dignity\u2014something steady, something that mattered to the city.\n\n3.\nThe phone call from MUNI HR came on a Tuesday afternoon. Standing in his small room in his parents' Sunset home, he listened to the formal job offer\u2014operator trainee. After hanging up, he didn\u2019t shout. He just sat on the edge of his bed for a full ten minutes, the silence thick with the weight of the future. It was the first time in his life he felt true, solid ground beneath his feet. This, he knew, was the beginning of his real life, a moment of profound, quiet pride.\n\n4.\nIt happened on an early morning 38-Geary run, about five years into the job. An elderly regular, Mrs. Chen, boarded and pressed a warm, paper-bagged pineapple bun into his hand. \"For always waiting,\" she said simply. The warmth spread from his palm through his whole body. It was more than a pastry; it was an acknowledgment. That simple act transformed his job from a series of stops into a network of human connection. He wasn't just a driver; he was their driver. He was seen.\n\n5.\nHe was driving the 1-California before dawn, the bus climbing the hill toward the Presidio. Through the huge windshield, he watched the fog ghosting over the dark expanse of the Pacific. The sheer, empty vastness of the water suddenly reminded him of photos he\u2019d seen of the Siberian steppe. In that quiet, humming cab, the vague notion of a trip solidified into a plan. He needed to see that other landscape\u2014not to find answers, but to simply stand at his own starting line."
